						<summary>

						<p>Slab lying in the jungle to the west of the village.</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">Rājabhū[shaṇa*] Sōmēśvaradēva Śaka 1019: 1097 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>This inscription may palaeographically be assigned to c. 11th century. The details of date Śaka 1019, Kārttika, <hi rend="italic">trayōdaśi</hi> tithi are not sufficient for verification.</p>						

						<p>The titles given in this record are found mentioned in the Kuruspāl stone inscription of Sōmēśvaradēva of the same date (<hi rend="italic">Ep. Ind.,</hi> Vol. X, pp. 37-38) except the epithet <hi rend="italic">Rājabhū[shaṇa*].</hi> </p>						

						<p>It records the gift of some lands (details are lost) by Kannarāju. The details of the land grant, the purpose, etc., are lost since the record is damaged very much. The witnesses to the grant are Bēti-seṭṭi, Malli-seṭṭi, Māni-seṭṭi and others of Bhairavadurgga.</p>						

						<p>The title <hi rend="italic">Rājabhūshaṇa</hi> is mentioned to have been attributed to king Sōmēśvara, not only in his own records, but also in the two Kuruspāl records of Dharaṇa-mahādēvī of the time of Sōmēśvaradēva.</p>						

						<p>(<hi rend="italic">Ep. Ind.,</hi> Vol. X, p. 32 and p. 34)</p>						

						</summary>
